"1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1590":"1590","1559":"1559","Banham, Norfolk, England":"Banham, Norfolk, England","England":"England"},"nl":{"1485–1503":"1485–1503","1483–1503":"1483–1503","1502–1559":"1502–1559","1503–1590":"1503–1590","1455–Male":"1455–Overleden","1460–Female":"1460–Overleden","1503":"1503","1502":"1502","about 1503":"circa 1503","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","about 1502":"circa 1502","about 1500":"circa 1500","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1590":"1590","1559":"1559","Banham, Norfolk, England":"Banham, Norfolk, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1485–1503":"1485–1503","1483–1503":"1483–1503","1502–1559":"1502–1559","1503–1590":"1503–1590","1455–Male":"1455–Deceased","1460–Female":"1460–Deceased","1503":"1503","1502":"1502","about 1503":"about 1503","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","about 1502":"about 1502","about 1500":"about 1500","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1590":"1590","1559":"1559","Banham, Norfolk, England":"Banham, Norfolk, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Oates","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): from the Old Norman French personal names <i>Ode</i>, <i>Odde</i>, <i>Odes</i>, <i>Otto</i>, <i>Otes</i>, or <i>Otton</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Audo</i>, <i>Odo</i>, <i>Oddo</i>, <i>Otto</i>), originally a short form of ancient Germanic compound names based on the element <i>aud</i> ‘wealth, prosperity’. See also   Ott   2.","Irish and Manx: adopted for <b>Ó Cuirc</b> or <b>Mac Cuirc</b> (see   Quirk  ), a personal name based on Gaelic <i>corc</i> ‘heart’, by erroneous association with the Irish word <i>coirce</i> ‘oats’ (Manx <i>corkey</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Quirk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Oona.","Manx and Irish (Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cuirc</b> ‘descendant of <i>Corc</i>’, a personal name from <i>corc</i> ‘heart’, or <i>curc</i> ‘tuft (of hair)’. The surname was sometimes Anglicized as   Oates  , due to erroneous derivation from the Irish word <i>coirce</i> ‘oats’. Alternatively, a shortened variant of   McGuirk  ."]},{"name":"Oats","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Oates  ."]},{"name":"Ody","meanings":["English (Wiltshire): from a pet form of the Middle English personal name <i>Ode</i> (see   Oates  )."]},{"name":"Oatts","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Oates  ."]},{"name":"Otis","meanings":["English: variant of   Oates  . This name is very common in America, but now rare in Britain.","History: John Otis emigrated from England in 1631 to Hingham, MA; he had many prominent descendants. His great grandson, James Otis (1725–83), was a Boston lawyer who played a major role in the development of opposition to the British crown and the establishment of the Fourth Amendment. Another descendant was Elisha Graves Otis (1811–61), inventor of the elevator, who was born on his father's farm at Halifax, Windham County, VT."]},{"name":"Ott","meanings":["German: from a short form of ancient Germanic compound names based on the element <i>aud</i>, <i>ōd</i> ‘wealth, prosperity’ (see   Otto   and 2 below).","English (London): from the Old Norman French personal name <i>Ode</i>, <i>Odde</i>, <i>Odes</i>, <i>Otto</i>, <i>Otes</i>, <i>Otton</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Audo</i>, <i>Odo</i>, <i>Oddo</i>, <i>Otto</i>), originally a short form of ancient Germanic compound names based on the element <i>aud</i> ‘wealth, prosperity’. Many of these names were Latinized as <i>Odo</i>. Odo was the name of the half-brother of the Conqueror, archbishop of Bayeux, who accompanied the Norman expedition to England and was rewarded with 439 confiscated manors. Compare   Oates  .","Chinese: possibly from Taishanese form of the Chinese name 達 (meaning ‘eminent’), a monosyllabic personal name or part of a disyllabic personal name of some early Chinese immigrants in the US."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sarah Oates was born in 1485, in England, her father, James Oates, was 30 and her mother, Mary A., was 25. She married Edward Bishop about 1500, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in 1503, in Banham, Norfolk, England, at the age of 18."},"et":{"1485–1503":"1485–1503","1483–1503":"1483–1503","1502–1559":"1502–1559","1503–1590":"1503–1590","1455–Male":"1455–Surnud","1460–Female":"1460–Surnud","1503":"1503","1502":"1502","about 1503":"umbes 1503","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","about 1502":"umbes 1502","about 1500":"umbes 1500","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1590":"1590","1559":"1559","Banham, Norfolk, England":"Banham, Norfolk, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1485–1503":"1485–1503","1483–1503":"1483–1503","1502–1559":"1502–1559","1503–1590":"1503–1590","1455–Male":"1455–Kuollut","1460–Female":"1460–Kuollut","1503":"1503","1502":"1502","about 1503":"noin 1503","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","about 1502":"noin 1502","about 1500":"noin 1500","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1590":"1590","1559":"1559","Banham, Norfolk, England":"Banham, Norfolk, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1485–1503":"1485–1503","1483–1503":"1483–1503","1502–1559":"1502–1559","1503–1590":"1503–1590","1455–Male":"1455–Décédé","1460–Female":"1460–Décédée","1503":"1503","1502":"